    {
      "id": "1dd0429946445e221e8c0cd8db59cd017eb66385",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-20 18:30:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAnn, could you please reply to my question?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c28d1c92b5365fa06621a6f0731d3519b0afbb18",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
        "email": "amk@cray.com",
        "username": "amk",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 15:01:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nSorry, Andreas. I wrote the reply but I forgot to post it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "06599bc45422241479ed68754b315096799da4c7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
        "email": "amk@cray.com",
        "username": "amk",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 15:07:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nHere was my reply:\nThat's Option 1 that I suggested in LU-9793/Jun 1 comment. I chose Option 2 because it matches the x86 behavior but there's a good argument to be made for Option 1 as well. If you think Option 1 is the better choice, I'll change the patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "82b7f0a031f52e9b400888e9405df14834f6e499",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-23 02:54:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> I considered your suggestion of passing through only ELDLM errors\n> unchanged as one possible solution. That's Option 1 that I suggested \n> in the LU-9793/Jun 1 comment. I chose Option 2 because it matches\n> the x86 behavior but there's a good argument to be made for Option 1\n> as well. If you think Option 1 is better, I'll change the patch.\n\nHi Ann,\nI also had problems with Gerrit holding my comments until they are submitted.  Note that you can click on the [Draft Comments] menu item at the top of any page to see if you have pending (unsubmitted) comments on a ticket.\n\nAs for the error returns, I think it is safer to not send unknown error codes from other architectures through, unless we have some expectation that they are the same on all systems?  That might actually be true for error values higher than a specific number, but I know for sure that lower-numbered errors (in the range 1-50 or so) are definitely different for each architecture.\n\nOne option might to be adding some debug to this code so that it prints a one-time error message with a stack trace if some unmapped error is returned, and then we will at least be aware of the need to fix it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "24758b2b78085c766944ef4a03aa0b93f17d9f9d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
        "email": "amk@cray.com",
        "username": "amk",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-10-23 15:52:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOk, I'll accept that mapping unknown errors to EIO is the safer choice. I'll rework the patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "24f025c13bd4889dc2923047089f2bc6f21bc29f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
